akashkarnatak.message:
Added Auth and touchpad activity.
Now main.py is the main server side script

A hidden password file stores the password which is required
to connect the android app to the server. "main.py" can be used to change
the password.

Now the app supports landscape mode as well.
Also tweeked the interface.

Now the app works for all android versions. Earlier the app only worked
for Android 8.1 or below because we are using Cleartext traffic which
is not supported in android 9 and above. Setting
android:usesClearTraffic="true" in AndroidManifest.xml does the trick.

Changed the interface.
Added left, right mouse clicks and also a sensitivity seek
bar to control the sensitivity of mouse cursor.
Further I have configured volume up key as left mouse click and
volume down key as right mouse click.

Fixed 'mouse pointer keeps on moving' bug. This is done by creating two
new variables "int start=10" and "int stop=-10" in the MainActivity.java.
The these values are assigned to "on_bit" variable.The starting
and stopping can now be detected in "sensor.py" by using if
statements.
Therefore, a boolean global variable "stop" is created in "sensor.py" which will
keep track whether start button or stop button is pressed. This variable
is coupled with the if-statement which moves the mouse cursor. This way
mouse cursor is stopped when the stop button is pressed.

Made the mouse movements smooth. This is done by equating some pyautogui
variables to 0, so as to prevent any delay in mouse movements and changed the
threshold of movement from 0.2 to 0.1 to make our app more sensitive.
Also changed the sensor delay value from SENSOR_DELAY_NORMAL to SENSOR_DELAY_FASTEST so
as to increase the rate at which json objects are being send.

Removed the checkNetworkConnection() function which only checked whether
smartphone is connected to mobile network or wifi. It has been removed because:-

1.) It can be easily tricked by connecting smartphone to a wifi which is different from the
wifi to which the laptop is connected. This way although smartphone and
laptop are not connected the app will not display "Not Connected"
message.

2.) If the smartphone is hosting the hotspot then the smartphone must be connected to
mobile network otherwise checkNetworkConnection() will display "Not
Connected" message although both smartphone and laptop are connected. This is wrong as the app does not
require internet connection to connect to bottle server hence the app should run without
mobile network.

So inorder to fix this I created a "notConnected" boolean variable which
will keep track whether the smartphone is connected to bottle server or
not. If the smartphone is not connected then
        String response = HttpPost(urls[0])  --> line 197 in my code
will throw error. Hence "notConnected" is set as "true" in the catch
statement.
Finally an if-statement in the "onSensorChanged()" function will display
"Not Connected" message if the smartphone is not connected to bottle
server. "Not Connected" message will be displayed even if both
smartphone and laptop are connected to the same wifi but "sensor.py" has
not been started yet.

Also fixed the app from crashing if "Next" or "Back" button is pressed
immediately after launching the app.

Fixed app from crashing when the 'Stop' button is pressed immediately
after launching the app. 'onStop' method does not have access to
sensorManager until the 'onStart' method is called. Therefore I moved the initialization of
textviews, ip_address and sensorManager to 'onCreate' method, so that they
can be accessible everywhere.

suchintan-p.message:
Matplotlib version needed

For previous versions of matplotlib, a traceback is observed while creating reports

Report in Tkinter GUI-new+some fixes

The changes made are:
1. To display report in Tkinter GUI, used FigureCanvasTkAgg to add the piechart figure as a widget to the frame.
2. A try-except block is added to delete (if any) previous figures in order to display the new report. Previously, the multiple reports were being displayed on the same frame as and when the user wishes to see them. Thus, after displaying three reports there was no space to display more. Hence , I decided to overwrite the reports in case of multiple report requests.
3. The statement self.root.after(...) is moved inside the if self.recording loop. This is done because when the recording stops, the statement shouldn't be executed. If it continues to execute in 'stop' condition, and the user decides to start the recording again, we see to separate self.root.after(...) loops running simultaneously. This anomaly was detected by observing the CMD log.
